This file contains the GPG keys of Gemini CLI maintainers.

Users can import these keys to verify the signatures of official releases:

  gpg --import KEYS

Maintainers can append their key to this file:

  (gpg --list-sigs <key id> && gpg --armor --export <key id>) >> KEYS

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Instructions for Verifying Releases
====================================

When a release is signed, maintainers will provide:
1. The release artifact (e.g., gemini-cli-v1.0.0.tar.gz)
2. A detached signature file (e.g., gemini-cli-v1.0.0.tar.gz.asc)

To verify a release signature:

  1. Import the KEYS file:
     gpg --import KEYS

  2. Verify the signature:
     gpg --verify gemini-cli-v1.0.0.tar.gz.asc gemini-cli-v1.0.0.tar.gz

  3. Check that the signature is from a trusted maintainer

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Instructions for Maintainers
=============================

To add your GPG key to this file:

  1. Generate a GPG key if you don't have one:
     gpg --full-generate-key

  2. List your keys to find the key ID:
     gpg --list-secret-keys --keyid-format=long

  3. Export your public key and append to this file:
     (gpg --list-sigs <key-id> && gpg --armor --export <key-id>) >> KEYS

  4. (Optional) Publish your key to a keyserver:
     gpg --keyserver keyserver.ubuntu.com --send-keys <key-id>

  5. Commit the updated KEYS file to the repository

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

